slipe
Homonym Number: 2
Word Class:noun
Sense Number:
Definition:farming: wool recovered from pelts in an abattoir or freezing works; wool recovered from pelts in an abbatoir by a wool puller after being chemically loosened with a sodium sulphide and hydrated lime mixture
Origin:
Register:
Register 2:
Flag: Farm Words
Domain:[none]
Region:[none]
See:
Pronunciation:
Notes:
Citations
Date: 0/0/1918
Source: NZ Journal of Science & Technology
Author:
Vol / Page: 1/165
Edition:
Quote:  The chemical action of this solution loosens the wool from the skin, and it is easily plucked off by hand. The wool (called `slipe') is then dried and packed in bales for shipment; the skin (now called `pelt') is washed, skivered, and finally pickled ...
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1982
Source: MAF Agricultural Glossary
Author:
Vol / Page: 59
Edition:
Quote: <i>Slipe</i>: Wool recovered from pelts in abbatoir. Body wool typed as woolly lambs, shorn lambs, and sheep. Oddments typed as seconds, thirds, and slipemaster. <i>Ibid.</i> <i>Slipe</i>: Wool recovered by a wool puller, chemically loosened with a sodium sulphide and hydrated lime mixture.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1982
Source: Collins Concise English Dictionary
Author:
Vol / Page: 1088
Edition:
Quote: <i>slipe n. N.Z. 1.</i> wool removed from the pelt of a slaughtered sheep by immersion in a chemical bath. <i>2. (as modifier): slipe wool.</i> [C14 in England: <i> slype</i>  to strip, skin] [? cognate with <i>slip, slippery</i>]
Notes: [1986 NZPOD 722; 1985 Collins NZ Compact Dict. 456]

